                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-25T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 25, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 25—4:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1225. Following from Tittmann.</p>
                <p>49, March 23. Possibility of a negotiated peace between Hitler and Stalin before
                    the summer is out is how a sign frequently heard of in <pb facs="0439" n="433"
                        xml:id="pg_433"/> Vatican circles. This talk seems to be based on Hitler’s
                    infinite capacity for double dealing, a sensation that the Russians will soon
                    become discouraged after the German onslaught begins and fact that a skillful
                    Japanese statesman has been sent to Moscow ostensibly it is said as Ambassador
                    but in reality in order to be on hand as mediator when the moment to discuss
                    peace arrives.</p>
                <p>I protest vigorously when I hear such talk as this and point out that matters
                    have now gone too far for anything like a deal between the Germans and the
                    Russians. I add that short of complete military collapse Stalin could not agree
                    to any sort of peace with Russian territory still in German hands and I urge
                    that the subject be dismissed as part of the German war of nerves.
                    [Tittmann.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
